# Da Infrastructure — Cursor Rules

## Context file
Always read `docs/PRD.md` before making any changes. It is the single source of truth
for product requirements, architecture decisions, data model, naming conventions, and
module completion status.

## Repository purpose
Terraform IaC for the Da dating app on AWS. Two environments: dev and prod.
No application code lives here — Lambda handlers are in a separate repo.

## Terraform rules

### File structure — every module must have all 6 files
- main.tf — resource definitions
- variables.tf — input variables (sensitive = true for any secret)
- outputs.tf — output values
- locals.tf — derived values (account_id, region, prefix)
- data.tf — data.aws_caller_identity.current + data.aws_region.current minimum
- versions.tf — terraform >= 1.5, aws >= 5.0

### IAM — non-negotiable
- Every aws_iam_role MUST set: permissions_boundary = var.boundary_policy_arn
- Every module that creates IAM roles MUST accept var.boundary_policy_arn

### SQS — non-negotiable
- Every queue MUST have a paired DLQ (7-day retention)
- Every queue MUST have a CloudWatch alarm on DLQ ApproximateNumberOfMessagesVisible > 0
- Every queue MUST deny non-SSL access in its queue policy

### SSM — publish everything
After creating any resource, publish its identifier to SSM:
/{env}/infrastructure/{service}/{property}
Examples: /dev/infrastructure/sqs/notification-queue-url
          /prod/infrastructure/rds/proxy-endpoint

### Naming conventions
- AWS resources (S3, SQS, Lambda, RDS, DynamoDB): da-{env}-{purpose}
- IAM roles: Da-{env}-{purpose}-role
- IAM policies: Da-{env}-{purpose}
- SSM parameters: /{env}/infrastructure/{service}/{property}

### Provider tags — always present
Every provider block must include default_tags with:
application_name, deployment_environment, deployment_source, project

### Secrets — never hardcoded
All secrets are sensitive = true variables sourced from HCP Vault via GitHub Actions.
Never use default values for sensitive variables.

## Architecture constraints
- No NAT Gateway — use VPC Gateway Endpoints for S3/DynamoDB, split VPC for Lambdas
- No ALB — use API Gateway HTTP v2 ($1/million requests)
- No ECS — Lambda only (chat service uses API Gateway WebSocket)
- No ElastiCache — use DynamoDB TTL for shared cache
- RDS Proxy is mandatory — Lambda + RDS without proxy = connection exhaustion
- Lambdas use arm64 (Graviton2) runtime — 20% cheaper, faster cold starts

## Backend runtime rules

- Runtime is Bun — set runtime = "provided.al2023" on ALL Lambda functions
- Always include the Bun layer ARN in the layers list
- NEVER set runtime = "nodejs20.x" — this is incorrect for Da
- Handler source files are .ts — Bun runs them directly, no compile step
- NEVER add tsc or esbuild build steps to Lambda deployment packages
- DB driver is `postgres` (pure JS by porsager) — NEVER use `pg` (native bindings)
- Middy createHandler() wraps every Lambda — never write raw Lambda handlers
- Secrets are in context (from @middy/ssm) — never call ssm.getParameter() in handlers

## Monorepo rules

- This is a Turborepo monorepo — root is da/, da-infra/ is a subfolder
- Run individual apps with: turbo dev --filter=@da/[app-name]
- Never run npm/yarn — always use bun
- All packages reference each other as workspace:* dependencies

## Mobile rules

- React Native uses Expo BARE workflow — ios/ and android/ folders exist and are committed
- NEVER suggest managed workflow — bare is intentional from day one
- EAS Build for native builds, EAS Update for JS-only OTA updates
- NEVER suggest Bitrise — EAS Build is the mobile CI/CD
- iOS in-app purchases: ALWAYS use RevenueCat + Apple IAP, NEVER Stripe on iOS
- Android in-app purchases: ALWAYS use RevenueCat + Google Play Billing
- Web purchases: Stripe only

## Local dev rules

- Local API server runs on port 4000 via Hono (packages/local-server)
- When adding a new Lambda service, also add its routes to packages/local-server/src/index.ts
- Local infrastructure runs in Docker — never point local dev at real AWS services
- Secrets in local dev come from .env.local via localEnvMiddleware — never SSM
- New secret needed? Add to .env.local.example AND to the createHandler() SECRET_CONFIG map
